%[text] %[text:anchor:T_0BF18B88] # Battery State-of-Charge (SOC) Estimation using Deep Learning in Time Series Modeler
%[text] In this example, you will create deep learning models for performing battery State-of-Charge (SOC) estimation using the **Time Series Modeler** app. You will load data, train and compare multiple networks (MLP, LSTM, CNN, GRU), and export the best trained network to Simulink for running simulations.
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%%
%[text] ## Open the instructions in a browser (Optional)
%[text] We have provided an option for you to have a separate window with the instructions for this exercise for a smoother experience.
open("Exercise_1.html");
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_18106281] ## Data Preparation
%[text] The training data contains a single sequence of experimental data collected while the battery powered an electric vehicle during four driving cycles at different temperatures (-10ºC, 0ºC, 10ºC and 25ºC). The test data contains four sequences of experimental data collected during driving cycles at the same temperatures. This example uses the preprocessed data set `LG_HG2_Prepared_Dataset_McMasterUniversity_Jan_2020` from \[1\]. You can download this data set manually from [https://data.mendeley.com/datasets/cp3473x7xv/3](https://data.mendeley.com/datasets/cp3473x7xv/3).
%[text] We have data stored in three different folders: Test, Train and Validation.
%[text] All data is already stored in ".mat" files, the input variables in a matrix X and the response variables in Y.
clear
if isempty(matlab.project.rootProject)
    error("No project loaded. Please load Aimbdworkshop.prj to proceed.")
else
    dataFolder = helper.getDataFolder();
end
%%
%[text] ### Load Training Data
%[text] We can choose from five features (voltage, current, temperature, V\_avg, I\_avg), where the last two (V\_avg, I\_avg) are the averaged values for voltage and current.
trainingFile = fullfile(dataFolder,"Train", ...
    "TRAIN_LGHG2@n10degC_to_25degC_Norm_5Inputs.mat");
[predictors,response] = helper.loadData(trainingFile);
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_767342F2] ## Overview of the AI Models
%[text] There are many possible choices for building the AI model. With three base predictors (voltage, current, temperature), we can train several deep learning architectures:
%[text] - **MLP** (Multi-Layer Perceptron): A feedforward network that processes each time step independently.
%[text] - **LSTM** (Long Short-Term Memory): A recurrent network that can learn long-term dependencies in sequential data.
%[text] - **GRU** (Gated Recurrent Unit): A recurrent network similar to LSTM but with a simpler architecture.
%[text] - **CNN** (Convolutional Neural Network): A temporal convolutional network that applies convolutions over the time dimension. \
%[text] The **Time Series Modeler** app lets you train and compare all of these architectures interactively, without writing any code for the network definitions.
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_TSM_TRAIN] ## Train and Compare AI Models with Time Series Modeler
%[text] ### Open the App and Load Data
%[text] Open the Time Series Modeler app from the Apps Gallery.
%[text] ![](text:image:7837)
%[text] or type the following in Command Window
timeSeriesModeler
%%
%[text] Click New button to start a new session. Import the `predictors` and `response` variables from the workspace into the app. Retain the default settings: 20% validation data.
%[text] ![](text:image:5c09)
%[text] In the **Observation Preview** panel, set **Type** to **Predictor** to visualize the predictor features.
%[text] ![](text:image:96e9)
%%
%[text] ### Try and Compare Different Models
%[text] **TODO:**
%[text] 1\) In the **MODELS** gallery, click **LSTM (Small)**.
%[text] 2\) In the **Summary** tab, under **Training Options**, set **MaxEpochs** to 50.
%[text] 3\) Expand **Window Options** and adjust the **Window length** and **Window stride:** changing both from 200 to 500. By reducing discarded time steps, this speeds up training but may affect results.
%[text] 4\) Click **Train**.
%[text] ![](text:image:5989)
%[text] Train for as long as you want, then click **Stop**. Alternatively, training will stop when max epochs are completed or any other stopping criteria are met.
%[text] 5\) Repeat the same steps for a few additional models: MLP (Small), CNN (Small), GRU (Small).
%[text] **Question:** Without changing any additional training options or model hyperparameters, which model provides the best accuracy? Which model takes the most/least time to train?
%%
%[text] ### Export the Trained Models from Time Series Modeler
%[text] To save a model and make predictions, select the one you would like to save (e.g., **LSTM (Small)**) in the model list, and click **Export to Workspace**.
%[text] ![](text:image:5caa)
%[text] As you export a model, it will be saved (likely) as `trainedModel_1`
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] trainedModel_1 = 
%[text] 
%[text]   struct with fields:
%[text] 
%[text]     TrainedModel: [1×1 dlnetwork]
%[text] ```
%[text] Extract the `dlnetwork` from the struct and name it as net
trainedNetwork = trainedModel_1.TrainedModel;
%%
%[text] ### Evaluate the Networks on a Held-Out Test Data Set
%[text] A key step in order to evaluate the network performance and for comparison of different networks is running inference on a separate test data set:
testFile = fullfile(dataFolder,"Test","01_TEST_LGHG2@n10degC_Norm_(05_Inputs).mat"); %[control:dropdown:43f4]{"position":[39,83]}
S = load(testFile);
XTest = S.X';
YTest = S.Y';

prediction = trainedNetwork.predict(XTest);
figure %[output:7408f48d]
plot(prediction) %[output:7408f48d]
hold on %[output:7408f48d]
plot(YTest) %[output:7408f48d]
legend(["network prediction","true SoC"]) %[output:7408f48d]
%%
%[text] ### Save the Best AI Model as a MAT File
%[text] You can save the workspace variable as a file in the current directory.
save(fullfile(helper.getCurrPartFolder("P1"), "trainedNetwork.mat"), "trainedNetwork");
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_715EA024] ## **Integrate the Trained Network into Simulink**
%[text] ### Export the network to Simulink
%[text] In Time Series Modeler, click **Export** then **Export to Simulink**. Choose a location to save your model (e.g. in Part\_1\_AI\_modeling), then click **OK**. This file location stores the model weights. Exporting to Simulink can take some time. The model will be saved (likely) as "`my_model.slx`" in your current folder, and will open automatically in Simulink.
%[text] ![](text:image:0a90)
%[text] Simulink displays the network as layer blocks. Data transformations like normalization that you use during training are included in the Simulink model.
%[text] ![](text:image:7a82)
%[text] To explore the network architecture, double-click the Model block. The Model block shows the network layers represented as individual layer blocks. This layer-level view is useful for debugging or exploring the behavior of the network in Simulink.
%[text] ![](text:image:7b1b)
%%
%[text] ### **Generate the Inputs for Simulink**
%[text] In Simulink, there are several ways how you can import data: "`From Workspace`" block, "`Inport`" block, "`From File`" block and others. We are going to use "`From Workspace`" blocks. We need to generate the inputs for Simulink in the correct format and we can use the left-out test data set.
steps = size(XTest,1);
t = (0:(steps-1))';
X_in = timeseries(single(XTest), t);
true_SOC = timeseries(single(YTest), t);
%%
%[text] ### Configure Model Parameters for Simulations
%[text] Open the **Configuration Parameters** dialog (or Ctrl+E) and set **Stop time** to the workspace variable named "steps" (which is the total number of simulation steps; this variable will be generated in a later section), and set the solver to "Fixed-step" and "Discrete" with a fundamental step size of 1.
%[text] ![](text:image:17bf)
%[text] Also, set the **Simulation Target** language to C++. And choose "None" for Deep learning library to enable library independent code generation. This will potentially accelerate simulation. Once done, click **Ok** to apply changes and close the dialog.
%[text] ![](text:image:6b0b)
%%
%[text] ### **Connect the Model**
%[text] In `my_model.slx`, delete the "`Predictors`" block, add two "`From Workspace`" blocks with "`X_in`" and "`true_SOC`" for the data variables, respectively. Connect the "`X_in`" input to the "`Model`" block. Connect the outputs with a "`Scope`" block.
%[text] ![](text:image:4416)
%%
%[text] ### Run the Simulink Model
%[text] Now we can simulate the model by clicking the **Run** button and double-click on the **Scope** block to inspect simulation results.
%[text] (You may check `myExampleModel.slx` if you run into any issues)
%[text] ![](text:image:2e14)
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_7BF2DEA5] ## References
%[text] \[1\] Kollmeyer, Phillip, Carlos Vidal, Mina Naguib, and Michael Skells. "LG 18650HG2 Li-Ion Battery Data and Example Deep Neural Network XEV SOC Estimator Script." Mendeley, March 5, 2020. https://doi.org/10.17632/CP3473X7XV.3.
